Women's under-17 medal basketball players fell short, finishing fourth
The third World Cup was won by the American women, who beat Spain narrowly 77:75 in the final despite 40 points by Angela Salvadores' Spaniard.
“We really wanted to win and not be potato, but maybe we wanted it too bad. We caught the start, but it failed to keep up because they rolled us under the basket,” regretted captain Karolína Malečková. “Playing in front of such an audience was a surreal experience,” she praised fans in Klatovy and Pilsen.
The Czechs started very well, taking an 8:0 lead thanks to two 3s and dominating on the field throughout the first quarter. At that point, the opponents seemed to be repaying defeat from the 85:88 base group after extra time. But the referees whistled them with 15 fouls for half-time, helping Hungary get back into the game with a 12:2 cord.
'I'm convinced it was enough to put in two more baskets, run away on 20 points and we wouldn't let it go again. But instead, our mistakes came. I'm not interested in the referees, but what we did wrong, and there were mistakes that helped the opponent get caught,” assessed coach Richard Fousek.
“It wasn't the first time we had a lapse in concentration. But the girls are fighters, they didn't release anything and fight to the end. The opponent was a lot of quality though,” he added.
In particular, Petra Holešínská was kept in the game by precise shooting from distance and pivotal Tereza Šípová. The top Czech scorer, however, had fouls problem, missing much of the third quarter on the field. The Hungarians took advantage of that, gaining a slight lead they had already held, despite the Czechs struggling until the final seconds.
'For us the first five games were a lot of challenging, we rotated matches in a close rotation and it cost us a lot of power. Already against Spain you could see the girls were tired and there was nowhere to take. Because of physicists, we haven't been consistent in defence. We didn't play a quick counter-attack, we lacked rebounding. And the Hungarians are of good quality that if you don't slide everything together, you're hard to win,” added Fousek.
He believes a promising future awaits his fiduciary. “In two years the girls were able to win the Youth Olympics, be second at the European Championship of 16 year olds and now they are fourth in the world. On our basis, this is a quality team with good character and needs to work with it and develop talent. Now it's up to the federation, which coach they will assign to them in the higher categories,” Fousek added.
