For the first time, Honzik's parents recorded that something was wrong with him, in a year and a half. He always looked into the space for a few minutes, immobilized and did not respond to anyone. Therefore, the pediatrician sent him to the pediatric neurological clinic, where doctors, after a series of examinations, made him a diagnosis of epilepsy and immediately put on drugs that did not work immediately.
It took almost a year for doctors to find the ideal combination of drugs that made him stop having seizures altogether. At the age of five, doctors dropped off his medication, and because the seizures didn't return, the parents thought Honza was healthy and started leading him more towards sports. He rode his bike, skied, played tennis and floorball, spending his free time playing games with his sister and mates. But he got another seizure at the age of 11, and everything started at once.
Doctors tried different combinations of drugs again, but this time nothing took up, seizures in the form of absences were constantly repeated. Since during the seizure Honza always stopped perceiving, his parents dreaded that he would get it while doing sports and get hurt. Gradually, Honza stopped cycling and swapped the downhill skis for cross-country skiing and snowboard. Although the sport provoked him a seizure from time to time, he never completely gave it up. He even made a dream come true and completed the Spartan Race, but along with a friend who kept him in plain sight to help in an emergency.
When Honz was 15 years old, his parents decided to try changing doctors and turned to experts at the FN in Motola. After a series of examinations, the doctors there considered that Honza was a candidate for surgery to remove a bearing from his brain - the source of epileptic seizures. “I had to do 2 surgeries in a row, first doctors put probes into my brain that sensed his activity, then they could only remove my bearing. It's been a multi-week hell for me. I just had to lie down and almost not move, wires were sticking out of my head that were connected to the computer,” Honza recalls.
The operation was successful and doctors removed the relatively extensive bearing. “The first days after the operation it was very mentally challenging, Honza was apathetic, confused, sad and almost not talking. Compared to how alive and communicative he is normally, it was a terrifying change, but luckily after a couple of days everything was back to normal,” the mum describes, adding: “He had 1 seizure a month and a half after the operation, but according to doctors, it happens. It's been three months without a seizure since then.”
This school year, Honza will graduate, besides sports, he enjoys languages and has started working with Company E, with whom he drives around schools for epilepsy beseda. Honza is not fully engaged in sports activities yet, starting to return to the sport a little time. “I'm learning how to play sports properly, how to breathe well so that I don't expose the body to sudden stress, which, though, is quite a nut with my competitive nature,” explains Honza.
This year, therefore, he is not actively participating in the traditional EPPI boating triathlon, at which patients with epilepsy and healthy athletes meet, which takes place this weekend on 28 September 2019 at Merry sandbox. But next year, I hope it will.
