Several years' suspicions have been confirmed to scientists. A team led by University of Vienna professor Philippe Schwablo published a study proving, for the first time, the presence of microplastics in human stool. While the study is small, with eight participants from Europe, Japan and Russia - however tiny particles of plastic measuring between 50 and 500 micrometres were found in samples of all those surveyed. None of the eight subjects were vegetarian, six of them did not shy away from sea fish, all drinking water from plastic bottles and food packaged in plastic.
And it would actually be kind of a miracle if nothing could be found. We already know that microplastics - which are produced either directly, for example, for the needs of the cosmetics industry, or arise from the decay of larger pieces - are present in marine animals, insects, tap water and sodas; in short, everywhere on the planet. Thus, their entry into the digestive tract of a person has only been officially confirmed. About 20 microplastic particles accounted for ten grams of stool, and scientists estimate that more than half of the world's population will have them in them.
Both lay and scientific awareness, of course, suspect that this is not well. But humanity still doesn't know how wrong it is - and what effect microplastics have on “host” organisms. Small particles can get up to the bloodstream or lymphatic system and end up in the liver, for example. 'It's the first ever study of its kind and confirmed what we've thought for a long time. Now that we have the first evidence of microplastics occurrence in the human body, we need to continue to investigate exactly what this means for human health,” Schwabl says.
So far, it is known that microplastics in the intestines can negatively affect the immune reactions of the digestive system and thus facilitate the absorption of poisonous chemicals and other pathogens into the body. And so far there is no known solution other than to limit the use of plastics, primarily polypropylene. But this will be difficult - the first task facing governments and authorities will at least be to stop its steep increase. As for plastic bottles alone, experts estimate that in three years mankind will consume a fifth more of them than it does today. The current pace is a riveting million bottles bought per minute. Each year, roughly eight million tons of plastic end up in the seas and oceans. The waste threatens marine ecosystems and infests the digestive systems of marine animals.
Some states have already acceded to restrictions and other measures, Kenya, for example - under threat of draconian punishments - has banned plastic bags. The European Commission is thinking about minor bans (well known straws), in the same direction the domestic Ministry of the Environment is heading. Critics, however, argue that such measures, while nice, are completely inadequate.
