Francis Fukuyama's history has bittered somewhat. In 1992, at the height of the wave of liberalism that followed the end of the Cold War and the fall of the Iron Curtain, this political scientist in his most famous book The End of History and the Last Man wrote: “That, what we may be witnessing... is the final point of humanity's ideological evolution and the universal acceptance of Western liberal democracy as the ultimate form of governance.”
Twenty-six years later, we are rather seeing how, from the US to Russia, from Turkey to Poland, and from Hungary to Italy, more illiberal models and thrive on different forms of nationalism, and radicalism. Fukuyama's current ninth book, Identity: The Demand for Dignity and the Politics of Resentment, is attempting to cope with the onset of these forces. As his interview by George Eaton for the New Statesman shows, he is reassessing many of his former positions: he argues that ideas of socialism should be rolled back into public space and Marx he was right in many ways. While at the same time, he insists that his thought development is still consistent with that of the 1990s, and critics are said to have misunderstood The End of History and the Last Man correctly.
“What I was already saying at the time was that one of the problems of modern democracy is that while it provides peace and prosperity, people want more than just that... Liberal democracies don't even try to define what a good life is. It leaves it up to individuals who feel alienated, see no point, and therefore associate themselves into groups according to identity that give them a sense of belonging.”
In its time, the book The End of History and the Last Man was written as a strong argument towards Marxists who viewed communism as the final stage of history. When asked about how he now views the socialists” boom in Britain and the US, Fukuyama replies: “It all depends on what you mean by socialism. If we are talking about owning the means of production, then except when clear services to the public are in demand, I think it will not work. But if you are referring to redistribution programs that attempt to solve the huge imbalance in income and wealth that we are seeing, then yes. I think not only could he come back, he should come back. That long period kicked off by President Reagan and Prime Minister Thatcher, and in which certain types of ideas about the benefits of an unregulated market, had in many ways disastrous effect.”
Ultimately, Fukuyama attempts to calm even the current situation, warning all liberals that even the onset of new not entirely democratic regimes will not mean the end of history.
