Bloomberg: Venezuela has hidden bitcoins and doesn't know what to do with them
Venezuela's central bank is conducting internal tests to see if it can hold cryptocurrencies. This responds to an instruction from the state-owned company Petróleos de Venezuela (PDVSA), which seeks to send bitcoins and ethers to the central bank and to then pay suppliers of this oil firms cryptocurrencies. Employees are also studying a proposal to allow the central bank to count cryptocurrencies in foreign exchange reserves, which are now near lows in 30 years. Citing information from four sources, the Bloomberg agency reported it.
Sanctions imposed by the United States on President Nicolás Maduro's authoritarian regime have largely cut Venezuela off from the global financial system. This has deepened the economic crisis in the country even further. Meanwhile, the current crisis is one of the most serious in global comparisons, forcing officials to use a mix of different ways to move money. While Maduro's bid to launch the world's first state-owned cryptocurrency has failed, ongoing efforts to use digital currencies show how desperate the government is to find ways in which to circumvent restriction.
Neither Venezuela's central bank nor PDVSA responded to a request for comment.
It is unclear how PDVSA came to its own bitcoins and ethers, nor how much value these currencies own. The business is having trouble obtaining payments from customers through conventional channels because big banks are unwilling to do business with entities subject to sanctions. Last month, the firm received most of a $700m (£16.6bn) payment in Chinese yuan because the parties failed to find financial institutions to allow the transaction.
PDVSA may not have the appetite to sell cryptocurrencies on the open market because it would require it to register on an exchange and undergo due diligence, so-called due diligence. Instead, he wants the cryptocurrency to be used by the central bank and paid with it to entities whom PDVSA owes. Officials at the oil firm believe the central bank is less exposed to any hurdles that might arise in payment by cryptocurrencies.
Bitcoins and ethers use a decentralized Internet ledger known as a blockchain to verify and record transactions. In some cases relatively anonymous transfers are allowed without the need for an intermediary. Few banks engage in digital currencies because of problems with money laundering and client information that goes with them and complicates compliance.
Cryptocurrencies are experiencing a return to the high ground this year after the 2018 debacle thanks to expectations of their greater adoption by institutions and Facebook's plan to come up with its own cryptocurrency. Even so, they remain unstable. Bitcoin has fallen nearly 20 percent over the past four days, however, since the start of the year it has a gain of about 130 percent.
Comment by Jan Šindelář: Manage the tracks as a company
Heavenly's election, while apparently not entirely smooth, is a round off to a sad tale of the state's failure to give the runways a clear direction. The board has been incomplete for over a year, and even after Wednesday night, that's not changing because one of the members has resigned. The provisionary lasts.
