Unusually open and unique image of Karel Gotta in Olga Špatová's documentary feature film
This unique film performance from Olga Šátová's workshop will premiere in Czech cinemas next spring.
“In mid-September last year, Ivanka and Karel Gott called me, and they approached me whether I would make a documentary about his life with Karl again after ten years. I didn't hesitate for a minute! Filming with a man who has endured more than half a century in the eminent Czech culture thanks to his exceptional singing talent, artistic humility and immeasurable industriousness was and is a great honour for me. The call to make a feature documentary film about Karl Gott, who has been bringing joy to three generations of listeners to his art, I accepted as a commitment to this legendary singer ,” director Olga Špátová describes her feelings.
Thanks to quick arrangements and agreement, the first filming day was already on 22 October last year, and the last footage with Karl Gott was shot a few days ago. The goal was and is abundantly clear - to capture authentically Karl Gotta as a phenomenal singer who gives himself away to his supporters, as a painter but at the same time a loving husband and father of his children. A man who for sixty years gives out joy with his songs to several generations not only in us, but also in Europe, and in fact around the world. A man who enrolled himself in the hearts and souls of his listeners by simply being.
The film is not meant to be a showcase for Karl Gotta's undisputed fame and his achievements. “Therefore, it is not even possible to compare my previous film Phenomenon Gott to this present one. Everybody is different. At least by filming them in a different stage of Karl Gotta's life, and this will be very much reflected in his personal, intimate confession that he gave us and which has put us all in what legend we have the opportunity to work and spend time, which is indeed indescribable,” adds Olga Špátová.
The creators captured Karl Gotta during his performances, during meetings with his fans in Hamburg, but especially in his home environment, whether in Prague, on a cottage in Czech Switzerland, on a villa in the Czech Republic , where he spent his childhood, and in other places that played an important role in his life. Thus, the film will be completely authentic and unique thanks to Karl Gotta's sincere openness.
“Olga has a great gift to film with her close-knit team so that we often got carried away by the spontaneous atmosphere and naturally let her into our privacy, which made me talk about topics fairly confidential. With her husband, cinematographer Jan Painter, they actually became part of our family. We originally wanted to feature the film in 2019, when I celebrated my life's jubilee. But because I had a beautiful summer with my family, I wanted us to shoot as long as possible. Well, and since there was a lot of me everywhere in 2019, my wish was that it be screened into cinemas in the spring of next year. This documentary film is a thank you to my supporters and everyone who supported and accompanied me in my profession,” Karel Gott himself says to the film.
