Library marks anniversary of death of Wenceslaus IV with exhibition of manuscripts
Six rare historical manuscripts from the turn of the 14th and 15th centuries, that is from the time of the Roman and Bohemian king Wenceslaus IV, can be viewed today and Saturday by people in Clementin Prague. The National Library released them from its vaults to commemorate this year's 600th anniversary of Wenceslaus's death. This morning, librarians and restorers placed rare originals in display cases at the Mirror Chapel. Admission to the exhibition is free; it is open for both days from 10:00 to 6:00 p.m.
An exhibition of charters entitled Ad mandatum domini Regis: From the royal office and library of Wenceslaus IV was prepared by the library together with the National Archives. The written heritage from the time of the reign of Wenceslaus IV is viewed by the National Archives from the point of view of official documents and the National Library from the point of view of literary works, its author Jan Vojtíšek said for the exhibition.
“Visitors can enjoy, for example, a work on agriculture by Peter de Crescentiis, which is essentially a kind of encyclopedia of agriculture, or a breviary, that is, a prayer book of one of Benedictine Monastery of St. George at Prague Castle, from the beginning of the 15th century,” enumerated the reasons why people should look at the exhibition, according to him.
The Epistles of Peter of Blois will also be exhibited, where a semi-figure of King Henry II of England is depicted in the introductory miniature H (enrico). The author of the decoration is most likely the Master of Samson's History, who also participated in the decoration of a number of other manuscripts alongside two volumes of the Bible of Wenceslaus IV. Visitors will also see John Wycliffe's Latin anthology of tractates dating from the period about 1411 to 1414.
Not one book has been preserved from the library of Wenceslaus IV in the Czech territory. This library was, according to experts, among the most extensive and also the most beautiful book collections in Central Europe at the time, because the young king was eager to build a representative library that would equate to the book collections of his French relatives. However, the library became defunct soon after Wenceslaus's death. Apparently, it was stolen or destroyed in the conquest of the castle by the Hussites. Several codes have been saved, though. The Austrian National Library owns the most today.
“We have a range of treasures in our collections and I am pleased that they are in a state that allows them to be displayed and made available to the public so called live and not just in the form of a digital library Manuscriptorium,” stated National Library Director Martin Kocanda.
On the day of Saturday's public holiday, an exhibition called What Hides Under the Floor will be open free of charge in Clementin, representing the archaeological discoveries of the area.
