Annex 6/Project management methodology
1. Project Charter
1.1 The purpose of the Project Charter is to define formal management processes and how to communicate between the Parties for the purpose of fulfilling the subject of the Treaty so that the implementation of the work or the provision of services is in compliance with the Treaty and this Project Management Methodology. The Project Charter shall make available to persons involved in carrying out a work or providing services the parts of the Treaty necessary to fulfil its subject matter. The charter of the project determines the occupancy of the organizational structure of the project, the method of communication, control and escalation mechanisms and the structure of the project portal on which all documentation is archived related to the execution of the work or the provision of services. The project charter will be drawn up by the project leaders and approved by the initial Steering Commitee.
2. Project organizational structure
2.1 The organizational components of the Project are (1) Project Steering Committee (SCP) and (2) Project Leadership (PVP) and (3) Work Teams. SCP and PVP are permanent organizational components of the project. Work teams are temporary organizational components of the project.
3. Steering Committee
3.1 The powers of the SCP/Steering Committee of the project in particular
3.1.1 approves the Project Charter; and
3.1.2 addresses escalated issues that have not been resolved at the PVP level; and further
3.1.3 addresses issues with an impact on the scope of the work performed or services provided; and
3.1.4 addresses issues related to the delivery schedule; and
3.1.5 addresses issues related to the remuneration or structure of remuneration for services rendered or work performed; and further
3.1.6 accepts individual deliveries, services, parts of work or work as a whole; and
3.2 The members of the SCP/Under the Order are the members of the SCP (1) the sponsor of the project behind the business and (2) the director of the ISIT division and (3) the head of the project. Under the Contractor, the members of the SCP are (1) the management representative and (2) the project leader.
3.3 The SCP/SCP meetings shall be held at least once per quarter. The exact days on which the SCP regularly sits will be determined by the project leader in the Project Charter. The SCP is always in the evaluation of a major milestone of the delivery schedule (e.g. initiation or termination of the acceptance procedure). The SCP shall always be in session if a project leader calls for the SCP meeting. The SCP sits in the headquarters of the Orderer.
3.4 The SCP Meeting Programme/SCP Meeting Programme and the supporting documents to be discussed shall be delivered to the members of the SCP by the Head of the Project for the Contractor, at least 3 working days prior to the SCP meeting. At its meeting, the SCP will always discuss the project status report and the draft minutes that are related to the acceptance of supply, service or work.
3.5 Right to invite experts and advisors/If a party deems it necessary, it has the right to invite experts or advisers to the SCP, but it shall communicate to the other party in advance and at the same time indicate the reasons why the presence of experts or advisers at the SCP meeting is expedient.
3.6 Vote/After discussing each item of the programme, the members of the SCP shall vote on the proposal submitted to the relevant item on the programme. Each member of the SCP has one vote.
3.7 SCP Decision with impact on the terms and conditions/Where the SCP decision relates to the contractual conditions under which the work is performed or services are provided, in particular where the SCP decision has an impact on the remuneration for which the work is performed or the services are provided, the Orderer shall, without undue delay after taking such a decision, prepare an appendix to the contract in question.
3.8 Minutes/From the SCP negotiations, the project manager shall draw up the minutes for the Orderer, who shall deliver the project manager for the Contractor.
4. Project Leadership
4.1 Powers of the PVP/Project leadership of the project in particular:
4.1.1 checks all outputs of each stage of the execution of the work or the provision of services; and
4.1.2 shall evaluate and refine the delivery schedule and the process of work in the execution of the work or the provision of services; and
4.1.3 discusses amendments which do not affect the text of the Treaty; and further
4.1.4 controls the synergies between the Orderer and the Contractor; and
4.1.5 manages the risks and corrective actions related to the execution of the work or the provision of services; and
4.1.6 escalates at the SCP meeting.
4.2 Members of the PVP/Under the Order are members of the PVP (1) the project leader and (2) the chief business analyst and (3) the application architect. Under the Contractor, PVP members are (1) project leader and (2) chief analyst and (3) chief architect.
4.3 The meeting of the SCP/PVP shall be held once a week, at the headquarters of the Orderer or in the form of remote communication.
4.4 The PVP meeting programme and supporting documents/PVP meeting programme and supporting documents to be discussed shall be delivered to the members of the PVP by the Head of the Project for the Contractor, at least 1 business day before by meeting PVP. At its meeting, the PVP will always discuss:
4.4.1 fulfilment of open tasks from previous PVP; and
4.4.2 the conduct of the work or the provision of services; and
4.4.3 fulfillment and update of the timetable of work; and
4.4.4 identified problems and how to solve them; and
4.4.5 the plan for the next procedure; and
4.4.6 risks related to the execution of the work or the provision of services; and
4.4.7 Evaluation and other requirements for the Customer's synergies; and
4.4.8 the status and severity of outstanding defects or incidents; and
4.4.9 Changing Requirements; and
4.5 The right to invite experts and advisors/If their presence is expedient for the effective course of negotiations, both parties have the right to invite experts and consultants or members of the project teams.
4.6 Minutes/From the negotiations of the PVP, the project manager shall draw up the minutes for the Orderer, who shall deliver the project manager for the Contractor.
5. Work Teams
5.1 Work Teams/Work Teams shall consist of the staff of the Orderer or the Contractor and, where appropriate, third-party workers. Working teams in particular (1) carry out specific parts of the work or services provided and (2) provide the know-how necessary for the execution of the work or the provision of services and (3) provide substantive and professional handouts for further decision-making.
5.2 The role in the working teams/The cast of roles will always adapt to the current stage of performing the work or providing services. On the Orderer side, the members of the working team are:
5.2.1 Business analysts of the substantive area/ areas
5.2.2 Guarant/key user of the area
5.2.3 Technical and Technological Infrastructure Specialist
On the Contractor side, the members of the working team are:
5.2.4 Chief Consultant/Analyst — Architect of the proposed solution
5.2.5 Consultant/Analyst
5.2.6 Technical Infrastructure Specialist
5.2.7 Developer
5.2.8 Tester, supervisor
5.2.9 Operating and Installation Specialist
6. A full overview of the cast of individual project roles and their communication matrices is determined by the Charter of the Project.
6.1 Communication Leadership/Communication in the project is mainly directed by the project leader Communication is always carried out in a factual manner with the aim of solving individual tasks, as quickly and efficiently as possible. Mutual, managed, communication of project teams includes in particular:
6.1.1 Project negotiations (SCP, PVP, consultations, workshops,...)
6.1.2 Acceptance and transfer procedures
6.1.3 Transmission and retention of tasks, information and documents
6.1.4 Registration of Change Requirements
6.1.5 Evidence of defects and incidents
6.2 Project meetings - program and background/Plan and to-do list from project meetings is always updated at the following meeting. The supporting documents to be the subject of the project meeting shall be sent by the project leader to the meeting attendees in advance according to the subject of the meeting. The documents are recorded and updated on the project portal.
6.3 Minutes of project meetings/From each project meeting, the Head of Project Order shall produce a written entry to the Manager the following business day after the project meeting Project Contractor.
6.4 Editing and supplementation of project meeting minutes/Editing and supplementing project meeting minutes by participants within 2 business days from the date of delivery of the minutes. Negotiations for adjustments and enrollment are directed by the project leader. Adjustments and enrollment are not a place to hold a discussion. After editing and replenishment work, the Manager of the Project Ends the Project Meeting Minute and Saves it on the Project Portal. The deadline for comment on the minutes of the project meeting may be amended by agreement by project leaders. Where any deadline for comment on the minutes of the project meeting expires without comments from the meeting participants, the minutes shall be deemed to be approved.
7. Risk management
7.1 Identification and registration of risks/During the implementation of the work or services provided, all interested persons identify and then manage in a documented manner the risks that may affect quality of outputs or deadlines for performing the work or provided services. Risks are recorded by project leaders on the project portal, including their severity.
7.2 Discussing the risks at the PVP/Discussing and Evaluation of Risk is an obligatory item for each PVP meeting. The PVP meeting provides for measures to eliminate or minimise risks.
7.3 Escalation/If there is a non-agreement or if a risk with severity affecting the contractual arrangement or schedule or reward is identified, such risk escalates the PVP at the SCP meeting.
8. Quality Management
8.1 The basic tool for managing the quality of project outputs is the acceptance procedure. The subject of quality verification is:
