Insects are up to sixty times less than 40 years ago
No other animal class is more represented in nature than insects. Beetles, butterflies and other species make up more than half the life on Earth. But reports are growing, according to which the insect empire is radically shrinking. Another scientific study on the subject came out just this week, and the situation, according to it, is even far more serious than mankind has so far been aware of.
The study is based on a field inquiry in tropical forest on Puerto Rico, in which American scientists copied a similar 1976 survey. As they write right away in the report's introduction, insects are “ten to sixty times less” in the forest today. This is the decline of the whole population, that is not the number of species, with the inquiry concerned not only insects but all arthropods. Due to insect extinctions, the population of other fauna that is dependent on insects in the food chain, such as birds, frogs or lizards, is also thinned.
The authors of the research put their conclusions in direct connection with climate change. The average air temperature in the forest has risen by two degrees Celsius over the past thirty years, according to them, and warming has become the driving force behind the collapse of the food chain. Thus, the study shows, according to the author's team, that the impact of climate change on tropical ecosystems may be much greater than previously predicted.
A big article in the Washington Post newspaper came out on Monday about the report, which makes the new findings right away in the headline as hyperalarming. “It's one of the most disturbing articles I've ever read,” entomologist David Wagner of the University of Connecticut, whose paper cites as an independent expert, told the paper.
Insect extinction affects Europe as well. “With us, the decline is also an order of magnitude,” points out Lukáš Čížek of the Institute of Entomology of the Academy of Sciences. However, in addition to climate change, the landscape changes that play a substantial role in Europe must also be taken into account. “We are just running for a significantly longer time than in Puerto Rico,” adds Čížek, explaining why scientists could measure such a rapid decline in the forest compared to the 1970s.
