Soldiers rehearse, pull down the curtains. China prepares celebrations at massacre site
The army rehearsed during recent weekends. Shops in central Beijing had to close and residents near the square were ordered to pull the curtains. Along the emptied streets, military cars rolled toward the square, and combat aircraft circled the sky.
Several Chinese told Reuters that they were proud that their country would put its military might on display. But one woman said it was hard to deny that the celebrations would unsettle other states.
She was apparently alluding to Taiwan, which China claims and where elections are looming. But there may also be concerns in the semi-autonomous city of Hong Kong, in which thousands of people repeatedly demonstrate against the China-based caretaker.
Celebrations are being prepared outside Beijing as well. The southern Chinese port of Xiamen had already put on a special light show on Thursday night. Xiamen lies across from island Taiwan and is among China's ten most innovative cities.
Ahead of the anniversary, there is a growing list of forbidden things. It already has drones, balloons, kites, alcohol, walkie-talkies and equipment using radio waves, The Guardian newspaper warned. He added that Weibo, a popular Chinese social network, erases “damaging political information.”
“It's another milestone, another opportunity to show that the Chinese Communist Party remains (at the oar) despite all the predictions,” said historian Maura Cunningham, who covers China. “It's a moment when the party can demonstrate order, control and power,” she added.
The People's Republic of China was formed in 1949 when the Communists led by Mao Zedong won in a fight with Chiang Kai-shek's nationalists who retreated to Taiwan.
In the second half of the 1960s, China underwent a disastrous communist experiment in the form of the so-called Cultural Revolution. In June 1989, Tiananmen Square regime massacred thousands of pro-democracy protesters from among students and workers alike.
Since the late 1970s, China has increasingly taken on elements of the capitalist economy. According to critics, it is now a mixture of the worst of communism (one-party monopoly and persecution of opposition) as well as (Dickens) capitalism (exploitation of workers).
