Renowned French chef Marc Veyrat lost his third Michelin star this January, a year after he acquired it. He intends to judge with the publisher of the red guide to receive the exact reasons for degradation. Veyrat also doubts the competence of Michelin inspectors, who he believes mistook saffron for cheddar. The first court trial is scheduled to take place in November.
The chef of the famous La Maison de Bois restaurant in the alpine region of Upper Savoy lost one of three Michelin stars in January this year. The publisher of the prestigious Le Guide Michelin will be judged because the commissioners' conclusion, according to him, was not properly justified. In addition, the removal of the asterisk according to him occurred without any notice. “I've been suffering from depression for six months. How dare you mess with the health of the cooks?” sent Veyrat to the commissioners.
Michelin is said to have provided the chef with only vague reasons, such as that the chef put cheddar in souffle, which did not like the inspection. “I put saffron in it and those gentlemen thought it was cheddar because it was yellow. From the beginning, I love working with Savoy ingredients,” he corralled against the Veyrat decision. The latter is convinced of the strong incompetence of the Michelin Commissioners: “You are crooks who only stir up controversy for commercial reasons.” An indignant Veyrat does not understand “how they could afford to say we put in our souffle cheddar.” “They insulted our region as well, my employees were crazy about it. We have eggs from our hens, milk from our own cows, gardeners collect fresh herbs every morning,” he exasperated.
The distinctive chef, always with a black hat on his head and dark glasses, is an opponent of a new generation of Michelin commissioners and is therefore requesting the removal of his restaurant from the red guide. However, the publisher rejects this. “If the business remains open and our inspectors re-select it, we will continue to recommend it,” argues Gwendal Poullennec, Michelin's international director.
According to Michelin, the chef's lawsuit testifies that he has no meaningful charges yet and the lawyer will only help him formulate it. “We regret that Mr. Veyrat communicates with us rudely. But we will examine his comments carefully,” he opined.
In addition to La Maison de Bois, Marc Veyart owns two other three-star restaurants.
